sections.english:
Then, Venerable Raṭṭhapāla, having eaten and cleansed his bowl and hands, stood and spoke these verses:

Behold this adorned image, a body erected from wounds;
It is afflicted, teeming with many intentions, for which there is no lasting stability.

Behold this adorned form, with jewels and earrings;
Bones covered with skin, it shines beautiful with clothes.

Feet are dyed with lac, the face is smeared with powder;
This is enough for the delusion of a fool, but not for one who seeks the far shore.

Hair is elaborately styled, eyes are smeared with collyrium;
This is enough for the delusion of a fool, but not for one who seeks the far shore.

Adorned like a new jewel-casket, a putrid body is decorated;
This is enough for the delusion of a fool, but not for one who seeks the far shore.

The hunter set the snare, but the deer did not approach the bait.
Having partaken of sustenance, I depart, while the deer-binders lament.

Then, Venerable Raṭṭhapāla, having spoken these verses while standing, approached the deer-park of King Korabya. Having approached, he sat down at the root of a certain tree for his day's abiding.
